LLMs combined with Model Context Protocol (MCP) tools are transforming how we approach business challenges, enabling AI agents to access real-time data and execute complex workflows that were previously manual processes.

WHAT: An overview of AI use cases relevant to Planning and Execution SMEs—highlighting where it's been applied to business and execution bottlenecks, and where it may have future potential:

Building Blocks

These core components connect AI models to Amazon's internal systems, enabling practical solutions to operational challenges. By providing structured access to data and tools, they help deliver measurable improvements to productivity and accelerate decision making.

Amazon Q CLI

Amazon Q CLI brings AI assistance directly to your terminal. It helps with AWS operations by answering questions, suggesting commands, and troubleshooting issues in real-time.

Access Methods

  • Q CLI: Command-line interface for terminal users
  • CLINE: VS Code extension for IDE integration

For installation and detailed usage instructions, see the Amazon Q Developer CLI Getting Started Guide.

Useful Setup Resources

  • Setting Up Amazon Q CLI with MCP on AmazonWSL
  • AWS GenAI Workshop Resources
  • MCP Registry Console

Model Context Protocols (MCPs)

MCPs are standardized interfaces that allow LLMs to interact with external systems and tools. They're what enable AI to move beyond text generation to actually performing actions in the real world.

How Q CLI MCP Architecture Works

  1. User Input: You type a question or command into the Q CLI
  2. Q CLI Processing: The CLI formats your request and sends it to the LLM
  3. LLM Analysis: The LLM understands your intent and determines which tools are needed
  4. Tool Selection: The LLM calls appropriate MCP tools with specific parameters
  5. MCP Execution: The MCP server executes the tool calls against external systems
  6. Response Generation: The LLM synthesizes tool results into a coherent response

Key MCP Concepts

  • Function Calling: LLMs identify when to use tools and what parameters to pass
  • Tool Registry: Central repository of available tools and their specifications
  • Standardized Interface: Common protocol for all tools regardless of underlying system
  • Composability: Tools can be chained together to solve complex problems
  • Extensibility: New tools can be added without modifying the core system

MCP vs. Traditional Integration

Feature Traditional Integration MCP Approach
Development Time Weeks/Months per integration Days per tool
Interface Custom for each system Standardized protocol
Maintenance High (each integration is unique) Lower (shared infrastructure)
User Experience Fragmented across systems Unified conversational interface
Extensibility Requires code changes Plug-and-play new tools

This architecture allows the AI to access real-time data and perform actions across multiple systems while maintaining a conversational interface. The standardized MCP protocol means new tools can be added without changing the core system.

Amazon's Internal MCPs

Amazon has developed several internal MCP servers that connect our AI systems to internal tools:

  • Outlook MCP: Enables AI to read, search, and manage emails and calendar events
  • Quip MCP: Allows AI to create, read, and edit Quip documents
  • SFDC MCP: Connects to Salesforce for account and opportunity management
  • Internal Wiki MCP: Searches and reads content from internal documentation
  • Phonetool MCP: Looks up employee information and organizational structure

These MCPs follow a standardized protocol that makes them composable and extensible, allowing AI to chain together multiple tools to solve complex problems.

Creating Your Own MCP Server

You can create your own MCP server to connect Amazon Q to your team's internal tools and data sources:

  1. Define Tool Functions: Identify what operations your tools should perform
  2. Implement API Endpoints: Create a server that implements the MCP protocol
  3. Register Tools: Define tool schemas with clear parameter specifications
  4. Handle Authentication: Implement secure access to your internal systems
  5. Deploy: Host your MCP server where Amazon Q can access it

With your custom MCP server, Amazon Q can interact with your team's specific tools and data sources, making it more valuable for your unique use cases.

Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG)

RAG enhances AI responses by first retrieving relevant information from a knowledge base, then using that information to generate more accurate and contextual answers.

This approach is particularly valuable for internal applications where the AI needs access to company-specific information that isn't in its training data.

In my experience, RAG significantly reduces hallucinations and makes AI tools much more trustworthy for business-critical applications. It's the difference between generic advice and specific, actionable guidance based on our internal knowledge.

RTS Checker

On July 14th, 2025, a power outage created an AWS Sev1 incident that impacted multiple Last Mile services. Drivers on the road were unable to deliver packages for more than 3 hours, creating a critical operational challenge.

Dale Baigrie
on a call with JT, Alperson and Arko - and mercury showing 20MM delivered, if thats accurate then it changes a lot... idk how to validate delivered real time... can u point me in right direction?
Jacob Merriman
Not to clutter this chat further, but, are other stations seeing issues with Mercury?
Alexandra Simon
yes my RTS on mercury keeps going up and down
Nikhil Ahuja
yash need to know asap man 🙂
Dale Baigrie
I'd suggest they give it 15 minutes for Yash to get back and sanity check the numbers before you raise caps.
Yash Shah
Sure

This was a time-sensitive decision with significant operational impact. We needed to quickly validate whether the Mercury system data was accurate enough to base our capacity decision on, but we didn't have a ready-made tool for this specific scenario.

Mercury Data Verification

Screenshots from the Mercury data verification process showing the cross-checking between systems

Prompt-Driven Solution

With time running out and our primary system showing inconsistent results, I used prompt-driven development to quickly build a tool that could validate the Mercury data.

The Prompt Used
I need help building a tool to scrape data from an internal Amazon logistics website. I don't know how to start, but I need to extract information about packages that have been returned to station (RTS) for multiple service areas and dates. The website is: https://logistics.amazon.com/internal/operations/execution/dv/routes I'm not sure how to access this data programmatically. Could you help me build a Python script that can: 1. Extract "Returned to station" package counts and details 2. Work with multiple service areas (which I'll provide in a CSV) 3. Pull data for multiple dates (today, yesterday, and the day before) 4. Have a user-friendly interface so my team can use it How should I start? What information do you need from me to help build this?
The Response Received
I'd be happy to help you build a tool to scrape data from the internal logistics website. To get started, I'll need some specific information about the website and how the data is structured. First, let's understand what we need to access: 1. You'll need to inspect the website structure to identify how the data is organized 2. We'll need to understand the authentication mechanism 3. We need to determine how to navigate to specific service areas and dates ### Step 1: Inspect the website Please open the logistics website in Chrome and follow these steps: 1. Navigate to https://logistics.amazon.com/internal/operations/execution/dv/routes 2. Right-click on the page and select "Inspect" to open Chrome DevTools 3. Look for the "Returned to station" element and right-click > Inspect 4. Share the HTML structure around this element so I can see how to target it ### Step 2: Check URL structure 1. Try changing dates or service areas in the UI 2. Observe how the URL changes 3. Share the URL pattern you see (e.g., does it include parameters for date and service area?) ### Step 3: Authentication details Since this is an internal site, we'll need to understand the authentication: 1. Does it use Midway authentication? 2. Are there any cookies or headers needed for requests? Once you provide this information, I can help you build a Python script using Selenium to automate the data extraction process and create a user-friendly UI with tkinter.

Following this guidance, I was able to quickly develop a working prototype that could extract and validate the data we needed.

Sort Plan Data Pull

Tool that extracts and analyzes sort plan data in real-time to identify:

  • Manifest over Forecast (MoF) variances
  • Planned double binning issues
  • Multiple Cycle Operation (MCO) stations

This helps sort planning experts make data-driven decisions to improve sort plan performance by accessing same-day, real-time data that isn't available in other data sources.

Key Features

  • Extract sort plan data for multiple stations and dates in real-time
  • Access critical attributes like SACO and sort plan run times not available elsewhere
  • Separate active plans, failed plans, and replans into different Excel tabs
  • Analyze MoF variance and planned double binning
  • Identify Multiple Cycle Operation (MCO) stations
  • Generate data-driven analysis documents with actionable insights

The tool provides access to critical metrics that were previously inaccessible or required manual compilation from multiple sources, enabling more timely and effective decision-making.

Program

Solutions focused on program management and documentation.

Kingpin Summaries

Using the Kingpin MCP to automatically analyze goals and identify:

  • Status vs. expected progress
  • Related dependencies and blockers
  • Recommended updates with supporting evidence

This has significantly reduced time spent on goal management while improving the quality of updates.

Example Workflow

  1. Query Kingpin goals for a specific team or area
  2. Analyze goal progress against timeline
  3. Identify dependencies and potential blockers
  4. Generate status update with supporting data
  5. Create recommended action items for at-risk goals

Email to Quip

Combining Outlook MCP and Quip MCP to create a workflow that:

  • Monitors specific email threads for updates
  • Extracts key information and decisions
  • Updates relevant Quip documents automatically

This ensures documentation stays current without manual copying and pasting between systems.

Benefits

  • Reduces manual documentation effort
  • Ensures consistent formatting and organization
  • Creates searchable archives of email-based decisions
  • Improves team visibility into email communications
  • Enables better knowledge management across tools

Agentic Workflows

While the prompt-driven approach solved our immediate problem, there's a more powerful pattern emerging: agentic workflows that can automate entire processes.

Workflow Concept

An agentic workflow uses AI to orchestrate a sequence of actions across multiple systems, making decisions based on the data it encounters along the way. Instead of a person reacting to messages and running tools, an AI agent can:

  1. Understand the goal from natural language instructions
  2. Identify the problem from chat messages or alerts
  3. Access internal systems to gather relevant data
  4. Run necessary analysis using appropriate tools
  5. Make recommendations based on predefined criteria
  6. Document the process and results automatically

Architecture Overview

Key Benefits

This approach is particularly valuable for recurring operational tasks that follow a consistent pattern but require judgment at key decision points. The agent can handle the routine aspects while escalating truly novel situations to human operators.

Future Topics

In a future session, we'll explore agent scripts - a powerful way to automate complex workflows with Amazon Q CLI and MCP.

What are Agent Scripts?

Agent scripts are structured markdown files that guide Amazon Q through complex, multi-step processes. They provide:

  • Step-by-step instructions for the AI to follow
  • Prompts for gathering necessary information from the user
  • Logic for handling different scenarios
  • Integration with MCP tools and local commands

Agent scripts are available in the AmazonBuilderGenAIPowerUsersQContext package and can be run directly from the Q CLI.

Available Agent Scripts

Development Scripts

  • pdd.script.md - Guide through prompt-driven development to take you from a rough idea to a complete implementation plan
  • code-assist.script.md - Help implement code tasks using TDD principles with Explore, Plan, Code, Commit workflow
  • unit-test.script.md - Generate comprehensive unit tests for existing code
  • idea-exploration.script.md - Explore and refine ideas through structured Q&A and research
  • **technical-design-document-generator.script.md** - Create comprehensive technical design documents

Code Review Scripts

  • cr-summary.script.md - Generate summaries of code reviews
  • cr-review.script.md - Help review code changes
  • **mcm-review.script.md** - Review manual change management checklists

Documentation Scripts

  • success-story.script.md - Write success stories for the GenAI Power Users wiki
  • readme-generator.script.md - Generate README files for projects
  • **api-doc-generator.script.md** - Generate API documentation from code

For a complete list of available scripts, visit: AmazonBuilderGenAIPowerUsersQContext Scripts
